      "note": "The chapter's rhetorical shape is tripartite: (1) legal analogy → divine application (33:1-9); (2) divine disputation with Israel's complaint, answered by case-law and judicial declaration (33:10-20); (3) narrative pivot followed by two oracles — one of judgment (33:23-29), one of pastoral exposure (33:30-33). The divine self-oath in 33:11 and 33:27, the recognition formula in 33:29 and 33:33, and the repeated 'son of man' addresses (33:2, 7, 10, 12, 24, 30) give the chapter its architectural rhythm. Ezekiel argues by accumulation: each section adds a new dimension to the same truth — individual moral accountability before a God who wants life, not death."
